PGP Frame Errors. The total number of PGP frames received in error. This should equal the rx_errors from the Firmware statistics.
PGP Frames Received. The total number of PGP frames received. This should equal with the rx_frames from the Firmware statistics.
PGP Frames Received (channel 0). Counts the number of PGP frames received on each virtual channel.
PGP Frames Received (channel 1). Counts the number of PGP frames received on each virtual channel.
PGP Frames Received (channel 2). Counts the number of PGP frames received on each virtual channel.
PGP Frames Received (channel 3). Counts the number of PGP frames received on each virtual channel.

PGP Cell Error Counter. This error counter increments when the lowest level PGP protocol quantum is in error. Examples of errors that would cause this counter to increment are, framing violations, incompatible protocol versions, CRC error, incorrect Cell size.
Last Received Opcode. The value of the most recently received Opcode.
Last transmitted Opcode. The value of the most recent command sent from the REB.

Link Down Counter. This should increment by 1 every time the PGP link transitions from UP to DOWN. Unfortunately, it does not use the LSST DAQ definition of UP, but rather only bits 1..0 of the state. Though normal initialization of the link causes only a single increment, on occasion a REB power cycle can cause the counter to increment more than once.

Link Error Counter. This counter represents a lower level error than the Cell Error. This error is caused by 8B10B errors on the high speed serial line such as disparity errors or symbol decode errors. Sometimes this counter can increment during the link establishment process, though I have tried to change the firmware to eliminate this.
Local Overflow Counters (channel 0). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the local side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Local Overflow Counters (channel 1). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the local side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Local Overflow Counters (channel 2). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the local side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Local Overflow Counters (channel 3). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the local side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Remote Overflow Counters (channel 0). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the remote side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Remote Overflow Counters (channel 1). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the remote side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Remote Overflow Counters (channel 2). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the remote side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Remote Overflow Counters (channel 3). These four counters measure the number of times the firmware on the remote side of the link has overflowed its buffers for each virtual channel.
Receive Clock Frequency. These quantities reflect the frequency of the clocks used by the Receive and Transmit sides of the transceivers. (Should be around 156.25 MHz)
Receive Errors. This is the highest level PGP protocol error. This counter increments when a PGP frame has been successfully received, but was marked with an error when it was sent by the REB.
Received Frames. This is the number of PGP Frames received from the REB. (I don't recall if it is mutually exclusive with rx_errors)
Description: Received Opcode Count. The number of synchronous commands sent to the REB.
Transmit Clock Frequency. These quantities reflect the frequency of the clocks used by the Receive and Transmit sides of the transceivers. (Should be around 156.25 MHz)
Transmit Errors. This counter increments when a frame is transmitted with the error bit set. (Analog to rx_errors.)
Transmitted Frames: This is the number of PGP Frame transmitted to the REB.
Transmit Opcode Count. These count the number of "synchronous commands" sent from the REB to the RCE. We do not use this functionality.
BDI Firsts count. The number of BDI pages marked as First (Start of Image flag is set.)
BDI Frees count. The number of BDI pages processed.
BDI Lasts count. The number of BDI pages marked as last (End of Image flag is set.)
BDI Null Pages count. The BDI woke up but no data was present.
BDI Overflows count. The BDI can report that its data buffers have overflowed.
BDI Sequence Errors count. The BDI can mark pages as coming out of sequence.
Bulk Data Interface Waits count. The number of times we have waited for a page of pixel data from the Bulk Data Interface.
Discards count. The number of times the Server tried to insert Image Metadata into the processing queue but failed to do so. (Presumably because the queue was full.)
No Event count. Upon the arrival of pixel data, there was no Image Metadata available to associate with it. The pixel data is discarded.
Wakes count. This counts the number of times the RDS server was awakened to put Image Metadata into it's processing queue.
Link In Reset error count. When a request cannot be fulfilled because the link is being reset.
Invalid Task ID count. A Response was received that does not have a valid identifier to use to pair it with a Request.
Link is Down error count. When a request cannot be fulfilled because the PGP Link is down.
Lists Posted count. The number of requests (Lists of register operations) posted the Server.
Register Operation Requests count. The number of register operation requests sent to the REB.
Invalid Task ID count. A Response was received that does not have a valid identifier to use to pair it with a Request.
Probe Counter. The number of times the RMS server has been probed by Clients. Normally this is once per posted list, but can also be done to detect the presence of RMS servers.
Register Operation Responses count. The number of register operation responses from the REB. Should be equal to the number of Waits and Operation Requests.
Orphaned Response count. A Response was received for which there was no corresponding request.

Task ID High Water Mark. There is a fixed number of buffers available to store outstanding requests while waiting for responses. If the REB does not respond to a request, then a buffer resource is lost. This counter reflects the largest number of outstanding requests. Currently, in a properly functioning system there should never be more than one outstanding request at a time, and the High Water Mark should never be more than 1.
Plugin Unopened error count. The window for this error to be encountered is very small. When a request cannot be fulfilled because the Plugin is not yet initialized.
Waits count. The number of times RMS has been presented with a PGP frame from the firmware.
